  "text": "HomeBeautyThe Gen Z-coded, hexagonal shampoos and conditioners debut at Target on July 13.Photo: Courtesy of GemzThe Gen Z-coded, hexagonal shampoos and conditioners debut at Target on July 13.After 14 years of research and development, P\u0026G is unveiling its latest venture: a new, water-activated hair-care brand called Gemz. Instead of traditional solid shampoos that function similarly to your average bar soap (i.e. lather, rinse, repeat), Gemz offers single-dose shampoos and conditioners molded into hexagonal \"Gems.\" Just saturate with water, and they activate into a creamy texture similar to that of a standard shampoo or conditioner.John Scarchilli, director of P\u0026G Hair Care, scientific communications, described the brand as \"a science-driven response to modern consumer needs,\" via email, explaining that \"each 'Gem' is made of intricately spun threads — creating a porous, high-surface-area matrix that dissolves rapidly when exposed to water.\"Photo: Courtesy of GemzBy cutting down on packaging and removing water (bottled shampoos contain up to 80% water), Gemz delivers a concentrated formula free from inactive fillers and excess product build-up to offer prolonged hair-wash results and the ability to tailor one's wash-day routine to specific needs.The brand will launch at Target on July 13 with five shampoos and five conditioners to address every hair type and concern: Shampoos include Perfect Air Dry, Touchably Soft, Up All Day Volume, Curly Days and Hydration Lock; conditioners include Quick Blow Dry, Profound Moisture, Rainy Day Anti Frizz, Stress Less Repair and Light as Air. A five-count pack retails for $8; the 11-count variety pack is $15.Photo: Courtesy of GemzAlongside its portfolio of traditional shampoo brands (Pantene, Herbal Essences, Head \u0026 Shoulders, Aussie), P\u0026G's expansion into innovative and sustainably-minded hair care is a response to shifting consumer attitudes.Scroll to ContinueRecommended ArticlesThe conglomerate observed growing demand for solid shampoos and conditioners, but felt that the market's current options fell short when it came to performance. \"Consumers are responding to the concept because it offers high-performance beauty results without the fillers, buildup or waste of traditional liquid formats — plus the customizable, travel-friendly design fits seamlessly into their fast-moving, ever-changing routines,\" shared Robert Reiss, brand vice president of North America Hair \u0026 Disruptive Innovation at P\u0026G.To introduce a new delivery system for shampoo and conditioner to consumers, P\u0026G is employing digital-first storytelling and influencer campaigns to snag Gen Z (its target audience)'s attention. It selected Target as its first retail partner due to its \"strong Gen-Z customer base\" that will help introduce the younger generation to water-activated hair care.\"Gemz was created for people who want hair care that adapts to them, even if their hair needs change every wash day,\" Reiss added. \"With Gemz, it's easy to mix and match formulas to create the perfect routine.\"Ahead, see all of Gemz's water-activated shampoo and conditioner offerings launching at Target.Gemz Want It All Variety Kit, $15Gemz Light as Air Conditioner, $8Gemz Profound Moisture Conditioner, $8Gemz Quick Blow Dry Conditioner, $8Gemz Rainy Day Anti Frizz Conditioner, $8Gemz Stress Less Repair Conditioner, $8Gemz Curly Days Shampoo, $8Gemz Hydration Lock Shampoo, $8Gemz Perfect Air Dry Shampoo, $8Gemz Up All Day Volume Shampoo, $5Gemz Touchably Soft Shampoo, $8Note: This article was edited after publishing to remove a mention of \"sustainability\" that P\u0026G deemed inaccurate, and to specify product names and quote attributions.Fashionista's audience includes 1 million site visitors, 110,000 newsletter subscribers and 4.74 million social media followers. Want to know how to reach them? Learn more.Subscribe to Our Newsletter",
